{
  "texts": [
    "Then, the sought partial equilibria f eq,w (t, A, w) are given by any distribution canceling out both terms of the Fokker-Planck operator Q p (f, f) that act on the opinion variable, i.e.",
    "satisfying the relationλ p ( Āω p + ε)(wρ Ā(t) -m Ā(t))f eq,w (t, A, w) + σ 2 p 2 ∂ w ((1 -w 2)f eq,w (t, A, w)) = 0,which, after computing the derivative with respect to w, leads to Beta distributions of the formf eq,w (t, A, w) = C(t, A)(1 -w) -1+ Āωp+ε νp (ρ Ā(t)-m Ā(t)) (1 + w) -1+ Āωp+ε νp (ρ Ā(t)+m Ā(t)),(22)where C(t, A) > 0 is a suitable normalization function ensuring that ∫ R×I f eq,w (t, A, w)dAdw = 1 for any t > 0.",
    "The partial equilibrium given by the Beta-type distributions (22) can represent two different scenarios:• none of the exponents of the distribution are negative, thus f eq,w (t, A, ±1) = 0 and, for fixed t and A, the maximum of f eq,w (t, A, w) is obtained for w ∈ (-1, 1).",
    "This situation corresponds to a consensus formation due to the compromise process of the binary interaction in (2) [13] (where full consensus would be associated to a Dirac delta distribution);• at least one of the exponents is negative, hence the distribution diverges.",
    "This situation corresponds to an opinion polarization inside the population, and it is commonly driven by a self-thinking process that is stronger than the compromise propensity [37].Clearly the formation of (partial) consensus is preferable over opinion polarization, and in general one would like to prevent the formation of extreme opinions."
  ]
}